One of the biggest reasons people fail on diets is Hunger. 
The goal should be to eat as much food as you can while still being in your caloric deficit.

Stop snacking on foods that don’t give you a lot of volume per calorie, as by the time you’re finished eating them, the only thing it actually did was make you crave more of it.

Instead, replace those high calorie foods with foods that are low calorie high volume/high nutrition.

I know fruits and veggies aren’t always the most “fun foods”, which is why we show you how to make them taste better cooking them in The BBP Pocket Coach @builtbyplants.io

Sauté your veggies, add your fav seasonings.

They’ll keep you full and on track with your diet

There are NO Good Or Bad Foods, just foods that are good to have at specific moments depending on what your goals are. 

If you’re dieting and hungry, the goal should be to eat as much food as you can while still being in your caloric deficit. 

Stop snacking on foods that don’t give you a lot of volume per calorie, as by the time you’re finished eating them, the only thing it actually did was make you crave more of it. 

Instead, replace those high calorie foods with foods that are low calorie high volume/high nutrition. 

I know fruits and veggies aren’t always the most “fun foods”, which is why we show you how to make them taste better cooking them in The BBP Pocket Coach @builtbyplants.io

♻️ SHARE THIS: If you want to Build your STRONGEST, best looking Physique… Beans, nuts, and seeds shouldn’t be your PRIMARY source of vegan proteins. 

🔑 Key word being PRIMARY 

Yes they contain SOME Protein in them, but the dominate in each of those are carbs of fats.

If you try to hit your Protein intake with those food choices while losing weight, you’re going to end up needing to eat so many calories of it that you’re most likely not going to be in a calorie deficit. 

Which means you’re not going to lose fat. 

Most, Not all, plant-based foods (Fruits & Veggies, Nuts & Seeds) are predominately higher in carbs or fats, not so much protein.

So let’s take a more strategic approach and Make sure you work in lean vegan protein sources such as seitan, tofu, tempeh, lentils & even protein powder @bbpsupps 

That being said, Definitely still include beans, nuts & seeds in your diet for their nutrient benefits, but view them as that. 

Not a main protein source, but it can be a supporting source since it has “some” protein.

♻️ SHARE THIS: If you want to Build your STRONGEST, best looking Physique being Plant based… nuts, seeds and beans shouldn’t be your PRIMARY source of vegan proteins. 

🔑 Key word being PRIMARY 

they contain SOME Protein in them, but the dominate macro in each of those are carbs of fats.

If you try to hit your Protein intake with those food choices while dieting, you’re going to end up needing to eat so many calories of it that you’re most likely not going to be in a calorie deficit. 

Which means you’re not going to lose fat. 

Most, Not all, plant-based foods (Fruits & Veggies, Nuts & Seeds) are predominately higher in carbs or fats, not so much protein.

So take a more efficient route and Make sure you lock in lean vegan protein sources such as my fav is Seitan. My homie Mike put me on to it when I first went vegan. 

This specific brand in the video is 70% protein. 
52 grams of protein out of only 300 calories. 

2 packs is 102 grams for just 600 cals. 

That being said, Definitely still include beans, nuts & seeds in your diet for their nutrient benefits, but view them as THAT. 

Not a main protein source, but it can be a supporting source since it has “some” protein. 

What’s your fav Vegan Protein?

Let me know below in the comments.

Let’s Talk About The Built By Plants Pocket Coach. The Number One Vegan Fitness & Nutrition App in The World. 

The BBP Pocket Coach App is our own social media platform specifically for Plant-Based people who want to be in a community of like-minded, driven people.

Some of the features of the Pocket Coach include:

1. Nutrition Calculator: Find your personalized calorie and protein targets to start seeing progress.

2. Virtual Kitchen: Access a wide variety of vegan recipes organized by meal type, with calorie and protein information for each meal.

3. Drag and Drop Meal Plan Builder: Easily create your daily meal plan by dragging and dropping meals from the Virtual Kitchen. It also shows your calorie and protein targets.

4. Grocery List Generator: The meal plan builder automatically generates a grocery list based on the meals you've selected, making shopping easier.

5. Mindset, Nutrition, and Lifestyle Courses: Gain unlimited access to our library of mindset, nutrition, training, and lifestyle courses. Develop the habits and behaviors necessary for long-term success and sustainable results. 

6. Engaging Community: Connect with like-minded individuals in our exclusive community, where you can share your progress and experiences, ask questions, and get support from others who are on the same journey as you and understand your plant-based lifestyle.

7. Weekly Sunday Sessions: Join Najee and the community every Sunday on a Zoom call to discuss progress, strategies, and participate in Q&A sessions. Sometimes, we even cook new recipes together.

8. Affordable Pricing: Start with a 7-day trial for just $1, followed by a monthly subscription of $27. It's a small investment for the immense value and guidance you'll receive.

These features are designed to provide and empower you with the tools, support, and knowledge you need to achieve your fitness goals and maintain a plant-based lifestyle.
